### Step 1: Create Theme Definitions in `packages/shared/src/themes.ts`

**File**: `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775394558751-9zw781/packages/shared/src/themes.ts`

This file follows the exact same pattern as `model.ts`: export types, constants, and pure lookup functions. No runtime dependencies, no React, no DOM.

**Types to define:**

```typescript
export type ThemeType = "light" | "dark";

export interface ThemeColors {
  readonly background: string;
  readonly foreground: string;
  readonly card: string;
  readonly cardForeground: string;
  readonly popover: string;
  readonly popoverForeground: string;
  readonly primary: string;
  readonly primaryForeground: string;
  readonly secondary: string;
  readonly secondaryForeground: string;
  readonly muted: string;
  readonly mutedForeground: string;
  readonly accent: string;
  readonly accentForeground: string;
  readonly destructive: string;
  readonly destructiveForeground: string;
  readonly border: string;
  readonly input: string;
  readonly ring: string;
  readonly info: string;
  readonly infoForeground: string;
  readonly success: string;
  readonly successForeground: string;
  readonly warning: string;
  readonly warningForeground: string;
}

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  readonly id: ThemeId;
  readonly name: string;
  readonly type: ThemeType;  // "light" or "dark" -- drives .dark class and resolvedTheme
  readonly colors: ThemeColors;
  readonly fontFamily?: string;
  readonly fontSize?: number;
}

export type BuiltInThemeId = "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight";
export type ThemeId = BuiltInThemeId | (string & {});
```

Note: The `ThemeColors` interface must have a key for every CSS custom property defined in `index.css`. The property names use camelCase; the mapping function (in the web app hook) converts them to kebab-case CSS variable names (e.g., `cardForeground` becomes `--card-foreground`).

**Constants to define:**

A `BUILT_IN_THEMES` array of 3 `ThemeDefinition` objects. The color values for "t3-dark" and "t3-light" must exactly reproduce the current CSS values from `index.css`:

- **"t3-light"** (`type: "light"`): colors match the `:root` block in `index.css` (e.g., `background: "var(--color-white)"`, `foreground: "var(--color-neutral-800)"`, `primary: "oklch(0.488 0.217 264)"`, etc.)
- **"t3-dark"** (`type: "dark"`): colors match the `@variant dark` block (e.g., `background: "color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-neutral-950) 95%, var(--color-white))"`, etc.)
- **"t3-midnight"** (`type: "dark"`): a new theme with deeper blues/purples -- e.g., `background: "oklch(0.15 0.03 270)"`, `foreground: "oklch(0.92 0.01 260)"`, `primary: "oklch(0.65 0.2 280)"`, etc. Uses entirely resolved color values (not Tailwind `var(--color-*)` references) since this theme has no CSS counterpart.

**Functions to export:**

```typescript
export const DEFAULT_THEME_ID: BuiltInThemeId = "t3-dark";

export function listThemes(): readonly ThemeDefinition[] {
  return BUILT_IN_THEMES;
}

export function getTheme(id: ThemeId): ThemeDefinition | undefined {
  return BUILT_IN_THEMES.find((theme) => theme.id === id);
}

export function getThemeOrDefault(id: ThemeId | null | undefined): ThemeDefinition {
  return getTheme(id ?? DEFAULT_THEME_ID) ?? getTheme(DEFAULT_THEME_ID)!;
}
```

**Critical consideration about CSS variable values**: The existing `:root` and `@variant dark` blocks use Tailwind's CSS variable references like `var(--color-neutral-800)` and `color-mix(...)`. When applying themes via JavaScript `style.setProperty`, these references still work because Tailwind resolves `--color-neutral-800` etc. at build time into the `@theme` layer. So the t3-light and t3-dark theme definitions CAN use the same `var(--color-*)` syntax. However, for "t3-midnight" (a fully custom palette), use resolved OKLCH/hex values directly to avoid any dependency on Tailwind's internal variables.

**Alternative approach (simpler)**: Rather than duplicating all the CSS values in JavaScript objects, only the "t3-midnight" theme needs explicit color values. The "t3-light" and "t3-dark" themes can have `colors: null` (or be flagged as `builtInCss: true`) meaning "use the CSS stylesheet defaults, don't override via JS". This avoids value drift between `index.css` and `themes.ts`. The hook then only calls `style.setProperty` when the active theme has non-null colors (i.e., for t3-midnight and any future custom themes).

I recommend this hybrid approach. The type becomes:

```typescript
export interface ThemeDefinition {
  readonly id: ThemeId;
  readonly name: string;
  readonly type: ThemeType;
  readonly colors: ThemeColors | null; // null means "use CSS stylesheet defaults for this type"
  readonly fontFamily?: string;
  readonly fontSize?: number;
}
```

