    className={`...border styles based on selected...`}
    onClick={() => setTheme("system")}
  >
    <ThemePreviewSwatch theme={getThemeOrDefault("t3-dark")} halfLight />
    <span className="text-sm font-medium">System</span>
    <span className="text-xs text-muted-foreground">Match your OS</span>
  </button>

  {/* Named themes */}
  {themes.map((theme) => {
    const selected = themeId === theme.id;
    return (
      <button key={theme.id} role="radio" aria-checked={selected} onClick={() => setTheme(theme.id)} ...>
        <ThemePreviewSwatch theme={theme} />
        <span className="text-sm font-medium">{theme.name}</span>
      </button>
    );
  })}
</div>
```

4. **Theme preview swatches** are small inline elements (not a separate component file -- following the existing pattern where the settings page defines everything inline). Each swatch is a `<div>` showing 3-4 color bars drawn from the theme's colors or, for themes with `colors: null`, hardcoded representative colors:

```tsx
function ThemePreviewSwatch({ theme }: { theme: ThemeDefinition }) {
  // For themes with explicit colors, use them directly
  // For CSS-based themes (colors === null), use representative values
  const bg = theme.colors?.background ?? (theme.type === "dark" ? "#0a0a0b" : "#ffffff");
  const fg = theme.colors?.foreground ?? (theme.type === "dark" ? "#f5f5f5" : "#262626");
  const primary = theme.colors?.primary ?? (theme.type === "dark" ? "oklch(0.588 0.217 264)" : "oklch(0.488 0.217 264)");
  const accent = theme.colors?.accent ?? (theme.type === "dark" ? "rgba(255,255,255,0.04)" : "rgba(0,0,0,0.04)");

  return (
    <div
      className="mb-2 h-16 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-md border border-border"
      style={{ background: bg }}
    >
      <div className="flex h-full items-end gap-1 p-2">
        <div className="h-3 w-8 rounded-sm" style={{ background: primary }} />
        <div className="h-2 w-6 rounded-sm" style={{ background: fg, opacity: 0.3 }} />
        <div className="h-4 w-4 rounded-sm" style={{ background: accent }} />
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

This is defined as a local function within the settings route file, consistent with the existing pattern (no separate component file for small UI helpers).

---

### Step 7: Handle the "System" Theme Mapping

The "system" concept must be preserved because users expect OS-preference sync. In the new model:

- Stored value `"system"` means: watch `prefers-color-scheme`, pick `t3-light` when light, `t3-dark` when dark.
- The media query listener in `subscribe()` remains unchanged.
- The `resolveTheme()` helper:

```typescript
function resolveTheme(themeId: ThemeId | "system", systemDark: boolean): ThemeDefinition {
  if (themeId === "system") {
    return getThemeOrDefault(systemDark ? "t3-dark" : "t3-light");
  }
  return getThemeOrDefault(themeId);
}
```

---

### Step 8: Verify Diff Worker Theme Sync Still Works

The `DiffWorkerPoolProvider` (line 32-33) does:
```typescript
const { resolvedTheme } = useTheme();
const diffThemeName = resolveDiffThemeName(resolvedTheme);
```

Since `resolvedTheme` remains `"light" | "dark"` and `resolveDiffThemeName` maps those to `"pierre-light"` / `"pierre-dark"`, this continues to work with zero changes. For "t3-midnight" (type: "dark"), `resolvedTheme` will be `"dark"`, so diffs use the dark theme. This is correct.

---

### Step 9: Ensure CSS Architecture Compatibility

**No changes to `index.css`**. The `:root` and `@variant dark` blocks remain as fallback defaults. When a theme with `colors: null` is active (t3-light, t3-dark), the CSS rules apply naturally. When a theme with explicit colors is active (t3-midnight), the inline `style.setProperty` on `:root` takes precedence over the stylesheet rules due to CSS specificity (inline styles win).

One subtlety: the `color-scheme` property. The `:root` block sets `color-scheme: light` and the `@variant dark` block sets `color-scheme: dark`. The `applyTheme` function should also set this:

```typescript
document.documentElement.style.setProperty("color-scheme", theme.type);
```

This ensures browser-native elements (scrollbars, form controls) match the theme type.

